#Hubble30 At the center of the Lagoon Nebula, imaged by Hubble in 2018, a young star 200,000 times brighter than our Sun is blasting powerful ultraviolet radiation and stellar winds, carving shapes out of the surrounding gas and dust: https://flic.kr/s/aHsmLztPS6
#Hubble30 Hollywood television producer @TreyCallaway shares how Hubble has inspired him and wishes the telescope a happy birthday! #HappyBirthdayHubble

Longtime Hubble supporter @SenatorBarb Mikulski has been a champion for the telescope throughout its career. Pictured here in 2009, she visited the Hubble team in the control center after Hubble’s last servicing mission. Today she’s sharing her birthday message for Hubble:

#Hubble30 These two galaxies, imaged by Hubble in 2017, are roughly 55 million light-years away. They’re similar in structure but appear at different angles. They offer a glimpse of what our Milky Way Galaxy might look like to an outside observer: https://flic.kr/s/aHsmLztPS6

To commemorate Hubble's 30th year in orbit, highlighted here are four extraordinarily talented and dedicated women behind the telescope who helped realize its success as a scientific game-changer and cultural icon: https://nasa.gov/feature/goddard/2020/four-successful-women-behind-the-hubble-space-telescopes-achievements
#Hubble30 For years, Hubble has helped @TheRealShantel look to the stars and beyond in her life and career! #HappyBirthdayHubble
Want more stories of Hubble? Check out the new mini-series, “Hubble, Our Window to the Stars.” Listen now: https://www.nasa.gov/content/hubbles-30th-anniversary-podcast

#Hubble30 Decades of planning. A devastating setback. Over a million mesmerizing images of space. The legendary story of the Hubble Space Telescope unfolds in @NASA's new podcast Listen and subscribe: http://nasa.gov/curiousuniverse

What astronomers thought was a planet beyond our solar system, has now seemingly vanished from sight. Instead, Hubble may have witnessed a cosmic collision that only happens once every 200,000 years: https://go.nasa.gov/34SLktO

#Hubble30 Hubble captured this view of the Bubble Nebula in 2016. The nebula is shaped by a star 45 times more massive than our Sun. Wind from this star sweeps up the cold, interstellar gas in front of it, forming the bubble’s edge as it moves outward: https://flic.kr/s/aHsmLztPS6
